The programme of the 2024 Summer Olympics will feature 329 events in 32 sports, including the 28 "core" Olympic sports contested in 2016 and 2020,[1] and four optional sports that were proposed by the Paris Organising Committee: breaking will make its Olympic debut as an optional sport, while skateboarding, sport climbing, and surfing will return from 2020.[2][3]

Accomplishments

[edit]

Individual events:

  • Eleanor Harvey became the first Canadian to win a fencing medal.[4]
  • Koki Kano became the first Japanese person to win an individual gold medal.[5]
  • Oh Sang-uk won South Korea’s first individual gold medal in men’s sabre.[6]
  • Mohamed El-Sayed won Egypt’s first individual medal in men’s Épée.[7]
  • Farès Ferjani became the first Tunisian man to win a fencing medal.[8]
  • Vivian Kong won Hong Kong's first women’s fencing medal.[9]
  • Manon Brunet won France’s first gold medal in individual women’s sabre.[10]
  • Lee Kiefer became only the third woman to win consecutive gold medals in women’s individual foil, and the first American to win three Gold medals in fencing.[11] [12]
  • Cheung Ka Long became only the third man to win consecutive gold medals in men’s individual foil, and the first person from Hong Kong to win multiple fencing medals.[13]
  • Lauren Scruggs became the first black woman to win an individual medal in women’s foil.[14]

Team events:

  • Japan's men’s foil team became the first non-European country to win gold.[15]
  • Japan’s women's foil team won their country's first medal in women’s fencing.[16]
  • United States’ women’s foil team became their country’s first to win gold in any team event, and the first non-European team to win gold.[17]
  • Ukraine became the first nation to win multiple women’s team sabre gold medals.[18]
  • Italy won its first gold in women's team Épée.[19]
  • Czech Republic won its first medal in men's team Épée.[20]
  • Poland won its first medal in women’s team Épée. [21]

Notes

[edit]
  1. ^ Individual Neutral Athletes is the name used to represent approved individual Russian and Belarusian athletes at the 2024 Summer Olympics, after the IOC suspended the Russian Olympic Committee and Belarus Olympic Committee due to the Russian invasion of Ukraine. The IOC country code is AIN, after the French name Athlètes Individuels Neutres.[22][23][24]
